full_input.content:
## Area 1: CPython gc.garbage / __del__ / legacy finalizers

### Key files
- `Python/gc.c` — GIL build GC implementation
- `Python/gc_free_threading.c` — free-threaded build (identical logic)
- `Include/internal/pycore_gc.h` — debug flag constants

### has_legacy_finalizer() — the decision point
`Python/gc.c` lines 678–683:
```c
/* Return true if object has a pre-PEP 442 finalization method. */
static int
has_legacy_finalizer(PyObject *op)
{
    return Py_TYPE(op)->tp_del != NULL;
}
```

### move_legacy_finalizers() — separates __del__ objects
`Python/gc.c` lines 685–713. Called at line 1537 in the collection cycle.
```c
static void
move_legacy_finalizers(PyGC_Head *unreachable, PyGC_Head *finalizers)
{
    PyGC_Head *gc, *next;
    for (gc = GC_NEXT(unreachable); gc != unreachable; gc = next) {
        PyObject *op = FROM_GC(gc);
        gc->_gc_next &= ~NEXT_MASK_UNREACHABLE;
        next = (PyGC_Head*)gc->_gc_next;
        if (has_legacy_finalizer(op)) {
            gc_clear_collecting(gc);
            gc_list_move(gc, finalizers);
        }
    }
}
```

### THE CRITICAL CONDITION: appending to gc.garbage
`Python/gc.c` lines ~1011–1039, function `handle_legacy_finalizers()`, called at line 1605.

The exact C condition (line 1030–1034):
```c
if ((gcstate->debug & _PyGC_DEBUG_SAVEALL) || has_legacy_finalizer(op)) {
    if (PyList_Append(gcstate->garbage, op) < 0) {
        _PyErr_Clear(tstate);
        break;
    }
}
```
- `_PyGC_DEBUG_SAVEALL` = `(1<<5)` — defined in `Include/internal/pycore_gc.h` line 128. When set, ALL objects in finalizers go to gc.garbage.
- OR `has_legacy_finalizer(op)` i.e. `Py_TYPE(op)->tp_del != NULL` — only objects with `tp_del` (__del__) get appended.

### gc_list_merge() — moving objects between lists
`Python/gc.c` lines 276–293:
```c
gc_list_merge(PyGC_Head *from, PyGC_Head *to)
{
    assert(from != to);
    if (!gc_list_is_empty(from)) {
        PyGC_Head *to_tail = GC_PREV(to);
        PyGC_Head *from_head = GC_NEXT(from);
        PyGC_Head *from_tail = GC_PREV(from);
        assert(from_head != from);
        assert(from_tail != from);

        _PyGCHead_SET_NEXT(to_tail, from_head);
        _PyGCHead_SET_PREV(from_head, to_tail);

        _PyGCHead_SET_NEXT(from_tail, to);
        _PyGCHead_SET_PREV(to, from_tail);
    }
    gc_list_init(from);
}
```
Splices the `from` list into `to` via pointer manipulation (no iteration), then empties `from`.

### tp_finalize vs tp_del
- `tp_del` = pre-PEP 442 legacy `__del__`. Detected by `has_legacy_finalizer()`. Objects with this in cycles go to `gc.garbage` — they cannot be safely freed (may resurrect or access other unreachable objects).
- `tp_finalize` = PEP 442 (Python 3.4+) safe finalizer. Called in `finalize_garbage()` at line 1066, BEFORE `delete_garbage()`. These objects can be freed normally.

### Full collection cycle order (gc.c lines 1534–1605)
1. Line 1537: `move_legacy_finalizers(&unreachable, &finalizers)` — pull out __del__ objects
2. Line 1542: `move_legacy_finalizer_reachable(&finalizers)` — protect objects reachable from __del__ objects
3. Line 1560: `finalize_garbage(tstate, &unreachable)` — call tp_finalize on remaining unreachable
4. Line 1566: `handle_resurrected_objects()` — deal with tp_finalize resurrections
5. Line 1574: `clear_weakrefs(&final_unreachable)` — clear weakref callbacks
6. Line 1581: `delete_garbage()` — tp_clear to break cycles
7. Line 1605: `handle_legacy_finalizers()` — **append to gc.garbage, merge finalizers into old generation**

### Python 3.4 / PEP 442 change
Comment at gc.c line 678: "pre-PEP 442 finalization method." Before 3.4, ALL objects with __del__ in cycles were uncollectable and went to gc.garbage. Since 3.4, only `tp_del` (not `tp_finalize`) objects end up in gc.garbage.

## Area 3: CPython set.cartesian_product() internals

### Key files
- `Include/cpython/setobject.h` — setentry and PySetObject structs
- `Objects/setobject.c` — all set operations
- `Objects/clinic/setobject.c.h` — Argument Clinic generated wrappers

### setentry struct (Include/cpython/setobject.h lines 20–23)
```c
typedef struct {
    PyObject *key;
    Py_hash_t hash;   /* Cached hash code of the key */
} setentry;
```
Entry states:
- **Unused**: `key == NULL`, `hash == 0`
- **Dummy**: `key == dummy`, `hash == -1`
- **Active**: `key != NULL`, `key != dummy`, `hash != -1`

### PySetObject fields (Include/cpython/setobject.h lines 36–59)
Important: `fill` (active + dummy count), `used` (active count), `mask` (table size - 1), `table` (entries array pointer).

### set_next() — canonical iteration pattern (setobject.c lines 710–731)
```c
static int
set_next(PySetObject *so, Py_ssize_t *pos_ptr, setentry **entry_ptr)
{
    Py_ssize_t i;
    Py_ssize_t mask;
    setentry *entry;

    assert (PyAnySet_Check(so));
    i = *pos_ptr;
    assert(i >= 0);
    mask = so->mask;
    entry = &so->table[i];
    while (i <= mask && (entry->key == NULL || entry->key == dummy)) {
        i++;
        entry++;
    }
    *pos_ptr = i+1;
    if (i > mask)
        return 0;
    assert(entry != NULL);
    *entry_ptr = entry;
    return 1;
}
```

Usage pattern (from set_isdisjoint):
```c
